00:19:52,800 --> 00:19:55,837
I even find the question distasteful.

253
00:19:55,920 --> 00:19:57,194
"Do you..."

254
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:03,118
Harold, please!

255
00:20:03,200 --> 00:20:06,670
"Do you have ups and downs
without obvious reason?"

256
00:20:06,760 --> 00:20:09,274
(Laughs) That's you, Harold!

257
00:20:11,320 --> 00:20:12,912
# Lord, my body

258
00:20:14,120 --> 00:20:17,237
# Has been a good friend

259
00:20:17,320 --> 00:20:19,470
# But I won't need it

260
00:20:20,520 --> 00:20:23,751
# When I reach the end

261
00:20:23,840 --> 00:20:25,796
# Miles from nowhere

262
00:20:26,920 --> 00:20:29,593
# I guess I'll take my time

263
00:20:30,720 --> 00:20:33,314
# Oh, yeah

264
00:20:33,400 --> 00:20:37,598
# To reach there #

265
00:20:40,320 --> 00:20:41,548
Psst!

266
00:20:52,360 --> 00:20:57,434
"Dearest brothers, let us faithfully
and lovingly remember our brother

267
00:20:57,520 --> 00:21:01,718
"whom God has taken to Himself
from the trials of this world.

268
00:21:02,720 --> 00:21:07,236
"God have mercy,
Christ have mercy, Lord have mercy."

269
00:21:07,320 --> 00:21:09,993
(All) Our Father, who art in heaven,

270
00:21:10,080 --> 00:21:11,957
hallowed be Thy name.

271
00:21:12,040 --> 00:21:15,953
Thy Kingdom come, Thy will be done
on earth as it is in heaven.

272
00:21:16,040 --> 00:21:20,079
Give us this day, our daily bread
and forgive us our trespasses

273
00:21:20,160 --> 00:21:22,720
as we forgive
those who trespass against us.

274
00:21:22,800 --> 00:21:26,998
Lead us not into temptation
but deliver us from evil.

275
00:21:27,080 --> 00:21:28,433
Amen.

276
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:42,992
# Bring tea for the Tillerman

277
00:21:43,080 --> 00:21:45,071
# Steak for the sun

278
00:21:45,160 --> 00:21:49,438
# Wine for the woman
who made the rain come

279
00:21:49,520 --> 00:21:52,830
# Seagulls sing your hearts away

280
00:21:52,920 --> 00:21:55,434
# Cos while sinners sin

281
00:21:55,520 --> 00:21:57,988
# The children play

282
00:21:58,080 --> 00:22:01,231
# Oh, Lord, how they play and play

283
00:22:01,320 --> 00:22:03,117
# For that happy day

284
00:22:03,200 --> 00:22:06,556
- # For that happy day
- # (Happy day) #

285
00:22:25,040 --> 00:22:27,508
My boy, excuse me.

286
00:22:27,600 --> 00:22:32,196
One moment, please. Who was that
old lady waving to you earlier?

287
00:22:32,280 --> 00:22:35,636
Hello, Harold. Can I give you a lift?

288
00:22:35,720 --> 00:22:39,872
There you are, madam. Were you the
lady who drove my car off yesterday?

289
00:22:39,960 --> 00:22:42,633
- The one with the St Christopher?
- Yes.

290
00:22:42,720 --> 00:22:45,871
Then I suppose it was me!
Get in, Harold.

291
00:22:45,960 --> 00:22:49,111
Were you also the one
who painted the saint?

292
00:22:49,200 --> 00:22:51,350
Oh, yes! How did you like that?

293
00:22:51,440 --> 00:22:54,273
- Well, I didn't.
- Don't be too discouraged.

294
00:22:54,360 --> 00:22:57,636
For aesthetic appreciation,
always a little time.

295
00:22:57,720 --> 00:22:59,597
(Tyres screech)

296
00:23:05,720 --> 00:23:09,030
What a delight it is, Harold,
to bump into you again.

297
00:23:09,120 --> 00:23:12,430
I knew we were gonna be good friends
the moment I saw you.

298
00:23:12,520 --> 00:23:15,034
- You go to funerals often?
- Er, yeah.

299
00:23:15,120 --> 00:23:17,793
So do I.
They're such fun, aren't they?

300
00:23:17,880 --> 00:23:20,075
It's all change, all revolving.

301
00:23:20,160 --> 00:23:22,230
Burials and births, all linked.

302
00:23:22,320 --> 00:23:24,470
The great circle of life.

303
00:23:24,560 --> 00:23:27,279
(Tyres screech)

304
00:23:27,360 --> 00:23:31,433
(Maude) This thing handles well.
Ever drive a hearse, Harold?

305
00:23:31,520 --> 00:23:34,080
- Yeah.
- It's a new experience for me.

306
00:23:34,160 --> 00:23:36,230
(Tyres screech)

307
00:23:37,480 --> 00:23:39,277
Well done, hearse!

308
00:23:39,360 --> 00:23:41,316
Shall I take you home, Harold?

309
00:23:41,400 --> 00:23:43,436
Er, this is my car.

310
00:23:43,520 --> 00:23:45,988
- Your hearse?
- Yearse!

311
00:23:46,080 --> 00:23:47,957
(Maude) Oh!

312
00:23:52,040 --> 00:23:54,713
Then you shall take me home.

313
00:24:08,080 --> 00:24:11,231
So, just before he left
for the monastery in Tibet,

314
00:24:11,320 --> 00:24:13,231
Big Sweeney gave me his keys.

315
00:24:13,320 --> 00:24:17,438
I had to make changes for the new
model, not as many as you'd think.

316
00:24:17,520 --> 00:24:22,275
Once you have you the basic set,
it's only a question of variation.

317
00:24:22,360 --> 00:24:25,272
You hop in any car you want
and just drive off?

318
00:24:25,360 --> 00:24:29,399
Not any car. I like a variety. I'm
always looking for a new experience.

319
00:24:30,960 --> 00:24:36,239
Maybe... Nevertheless,
I think you're upsetting people.

320
00:24:36,320 --> 00:24:38,276
I don't know if that's right.

321
00:24:39,560 --> 00:24:43,553
If people get upset cos they feel
they have a hold on some things,

322
00:24:43,640 --> 00:24:47,713
I'm just acting as a gentle reminder,
here today, gone tomorrow.

323
00:24:47,800 --> 00:24:51,349
So don't get attached to things.
Now, with that in mind,

324
00:24:51,440 --> 00:24:53,590
I'm not against collecting stuff.

325
00:24:53,680 --> 00:24:57,355
I've collected quite
a lot of stuff in my time.

326
00:24:58,640 --> 00:25:01,234
This is all memorabilia

327
00:25:01,320 --> 00:25:05,393
but it's incidental, not integral,
if you know what I mean.

328
00:25:05,480 --> 00:25:08,074
- Oh! The birds.
- Wow!

329
00:25:08,160 --> 00:25:10,116
I love them so much.

330
00:25:10,720 --> 00:25:13,871
They are the only wildlife
I get to see any more.

331
00:25:13,960 --> 00:25:16,599
Ah, me, free as a bird.

332
00:25:18,720 --> 00:25:23,157
At one time, I used to break into
pet shops to liberate the canaries

333
00:25:23,240 --> 00:25:26,516
but I decided that was an idea
way before its time.

334
00:25:26,600 --> 00:25:30,434
Zoos are full,
prisons are overflowing.

335
00:25:30,520 --> 00:25:34,752
Oh, my, how the world still...

336
00:25:34,840 --> 00:25:37,149
dearly loves a cage.

337
00:25:37,240 --> 00:25:39,117
Er, please sit down, Harold.

338
00:25:39,200 --> 00:25:42,829
I'll put the kettle on.
We'll have a nice, hot cup of tea.

339
00:25:42,920 --> 00:25:44,911
Thank you but I really have to go.

340
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:48,310
Oh! But it's oat straw tea!
You've not had that, have you?

341
00:25:48,400 --> 00:25:50,709
- No.
- Well, then.

342
00:25:50,800 --> 00:25:53,633
I really do have to go.
I have an appointment.

343
00:25:53,720 --> 00:25:57,793
- I really can't miss it.
- Ah... at the dentist?

344
00:25:59,240 --> 00:26:01,117
Kind of.

345
00:26:02,200 --> 00:26:04,998
Well, you'll just have to come back
and visit.

346
00:26:05,080 --> 00:26:07,958
- All right.
- My door's always open.

347
00:26:08,040 --> 00:26:10,395
- All right.
- Promise?

348
00:26:10,480 --> 00:26:11,708
I promise.

349
00:26:15,080 --> 00:26:16,718
(Psychiatrist) Harold.

350
00:26:18,200 --> 00:26:19,792
Harold?

351
00:26:20,960 --> 00:26:23,554
I asked, do you have any friends?

352
00:26:23,640 --> 00:26:26,552
- No.
- None at all?

353
00:26:26,640 --> 00:26:28,676
No.

354
00:26:28,760 --> 00:26:30,830
Maybe one.

355
00:26:30,920 --> 00:26:33,309
Would you care to talk about
this friend?

356
00:26:33,400 --> 00:26:34,799
No!

357
00:26:34,880 --> 00:26:38,793
You are an interesting case
but this reluctance is detrimental

358
00:26:38,880 --> 00:26:41,075
to the psychoanalytical process.

359
00:26:41,160 --> 00:26:43,230
Do you understand?

360
00:26:46,640 --> 00:26:48,517
Very well.

361
00:26:48,600 --> 00:26:52,593
Your mother tells me that she's
arranging several dates for you

362
00:26:52,680 --> 00:26:54,318
with some young ladies.

363
00:26:54,400 --> 00:26:56,516
How do you feel about that?

364
00:26:56,600 --> 00:26:59,034
(Snoring)

365
00:27:02,520 --> 00:27:06,195
- Hello, I'm Candy Gulf.
- How do you do? I'm Mrs Chasen.

366
00:27:06,280 --> 00:27:10,273
Do come in. Harold's in the garden
but he'll be here in a moment.

367
00:27:10,360 --> 00:27:12,271
Shall we sit down?

368
00:27:12,360 --> 00:27:14,396
Oh! There's Harold.

369
00:27:14,480 --> 00:27:15,754
Harold!

370
00:27:19,840 --> 00:27:23,469
(Giggling) Oh, he seems very nice.

371
00:27:23,560 --> 00:27:25,198
Oh, thank you.

372
00:27:25,280 --> 00:27:28,670
- You are at the university?
- Yes, I am.

373
00:27:28,760 --> 00:27:32,435
- What are you studying?
- Poli Sci with a minor in Home Ec.

374
00:27:32,520 --> 00:27:34,158
Poli Sci?

375
00:27:34,240 --> 00:27:37,789
Political Science.
It's all about what's going on.

376
00:27:37,880 --> 00:27:40,872
Is Harold interested in
what's going on?

377
00:27:40,960 --> 00:27:43,838
I just think
it's such a super thing to study

378
00:27:43,920 --> 00:27:46,673
and I can always fall back
on my Home Ec.

379
00:27:46,760 --> 00:27:48,796
- That's good planning.
- Yes.

380
00:27:48,880 --> 00:27:52,236
Tell me, are you a regular
with this Computer Club?

381
00:27:52,320 --> 00:27:55,517
Heavens, no!
I don't have to worry about dates.

382
00:27:55,600 --> 00:27:57,556
Oh!

383
00:27:57,640 --> 00:28:02,111
Some of the girls in my sorority
decided that someone ought to try it

384
00:28:02,200 --> 00:28:05,192
- so we drew straws and I lost!
- Oh!

385
00:28:05,280 --> 00:28:08,511
Oh, but I'm looking forward to
meeting Harold.

386
00:28:08,600 --> 00:28:13,833
I should mention, Candy, Harold does
have his little eccentric moments.

387
00:28:13,920 --> 00:28:17,913
That's all right. I have a brother
who's a real cut-up, too.

388
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:21,037
Oh! I will never forget the time,

389
00:28:21,120 --> 00:28:24,157
we had this old TV set
with no parts in it,

390
00:28:24,240 --> 00:28:28,597
Tommy stuck his head behind it
and started giving a whole newscast

391
00:28:28,680 --> 00:28:30,636
before the entire family!

392
00:28:30,720 --> 00:28:32,597
Must have been very funny.

393
00:28:34,480 --> 00:28:37,313
Ah! Harold! Oh!

394
00:28:37,400 --> 00:28:39,356
Yes, dear, here is Harold now.

395
00:28:39,440 --> 00:28:41,476
Harold, this is Candy.

396
00:28:41,560 --> 00:28:45,155
Candy's just been telling us
a funny story about...

397
00:28:46,360 --> 00:28:48,032
Walter Cronkite.

398
00:28:51,360 --> 00:28:53,112
(Candy shrieking)

399
00:28:59,960 --> 00:29:02,235
# I used to walk alone

400
00:29:02,320 --> 00:29:04,356
# Every step seemed the same

401
00:29:07,760 --> 00:29:09,796
# This world was not my home

402
00:29:09,880 --> 00:29:12,792
# So there was nothing much to gain

403
00:29:15,640 --> 00:29:17,631
# Look up and see the clouds

404
00:29:17,720 --> 00:29:21,679
# Look down and see the cold floor

405
00:29:23,920 --> 00:29:26,115
# Until you came into my life, girl

406
00:29:26,200 --> 00:29:28,794
# I saw nothing, nothing more #

407
00:29:34,400 --> 00:29:37,153
Oh... Excuse me.

408
00:29:39,480 --> 00:29:42,711
- I beg your pardon.
- What do you want?

409
00:29:42,800 --> 00:29:45,439
I'm sorry, I was looking for Maude.

410
00:29:45,520 --> 00:29:47,078
(Maude) Harold?

411
00:29:50,640 --> 00:29:52,631
(Simpers)

412
00:29:52,720 --> 00:29:54,472
Maude.

413
00:29:55,800 --> 00:29:57,756
How about some ginger pie?

414
00:29:58,800 --> 00:30:01,314
- Fine. Thank you.
- I'll heat some up.

415
00:30:04,800 --> 00:30:07,234
My, Harold,
I'm glad to see you again.

416
00:30:07,320 --> 00:30:09,356
Do you often model for Glaucus?

417
00:30:09,440 --> 00:30:12,193
Oh, heavens, no!
I don't have the time

418
00:30:12,280 --> 00:30:14,111
but I like to keep in practice

419
00:30:14,200 --> 00:30:18,159
and poor Glaucus occasionally
needs his memory refreshed

420
00:30:18,240 --> 00:30:20,754
as to the contours
of the female form.

421
00:30:22,120 --> 00:30:25,237
- Do you disapprove?
- Me? No, of course not.

422
00:30:27,520 --> 00:30:31,035
Really? Do you think it's wrong?

423
00:30:41,240 --> 00:30:42,309
No.

424
00:30:42,400 --> 00:30:44,755
Oh, heavens! I'm glad you said that.

425
00:30:44,840 --> 00:30:49,675
I wanna show you my painting.
This is The Rape Of Rome.

426
00:30:50,840 --> 00:30:54,276
Over in the corner
is Leda And The Swan,

427
00:30:54,360 --> 00:30:56,635
self-portrait,

428
00:30:56,720 --> 00:30:58,950
and over here is my favourite.

429
00:31:01,120 --> 00:31:07,229
It's titled... Rainbow With
Egg Underneath And An Elephant.

430
00:31:08,280 --> 00:31:11,158
- Do you like it?
- Oh, yeah, very much.

431
00:31:11,240 --> 00:31:15,597
I then became infatuated with these,
my odorifics.

432
00:31:15,680 --> 00:31:20,231
Give the nose a treat!
A kind of a... olfactory banquet.

433
00:31:20,320 --> 00:31:24,359
So, I began on the easiest -
roast beef, old books, mown grass

434
00:31:24,440 --> 00:31:26,351
and Mexican farmyard.

435
00:31:26,440 --> 00:31:31,309
Oh! Here's one you'll like,
Snowfall on 42nd Street.

436
00:31:31,400 --> 00:31:33,675
I'll put it on.

437
00:31:34,880 --> 00:31:38,668
Now, er, you hold onto this,
I'll pump it up.

438
00:31:39,560 --> 00:31:41,471
(Whirring and gurgling)

439
00:31:41,560 --> 00:31:44,074
OK, now hold it up there.
That's right.

440
00:31:44,160 --> 00:31:46,116
Now, what do you smell?

441
00:31:50,600 --> 00:31:52,158
Subways?

442
00:31:52,240 --> 00:31:53,912
(Laughs)

443
00:31:55,400 --> 00:31:57,277
(Breathes in deeply)

444
00:31:58,680 --> 00:32:00,830
Perfume?

445
00:32:00,920 --> 00:32:03,434
(Breathes in deeply)

446
00:32:06,240 --> 00:32:08,515
- Cigarettes!
- (Laughs)

447
00:32:08,600 --> 00:32:10,591
(Breathes in deeply)

448
00:32:15,880 --> 00:32:18,713
- Snow.
- Sn!

449
00:32:18,800 --> 00:32:21,189
Oh, it goes on and on.

450
00:32:22,320 --> 00:32:23,673
It's just great.

451
00:32:23,760 --> 00:32:28,436
But... then I decided
to switch to the tactile.

452
00:32:31,040 --> 00:32:34,350
- What do you think?
- I like this.

453
00:32:34,440 --> 00:32:38,558
No, no, really get close
and reach in and feel.

454
00:32:38,640 --> 00:32:41,359
- (Whistling)
- Oh! There's my kettle.

455
00:32:41,440 --> 00:32:45,149
Er, well... stroke...

456
00:32:45,240 --> 00:32:50,155
palm... caress... explore.

457
00:33:22,200 --> 00:33:24,589
(Harold moaning with pleasure)

458
00:33:24,680 --> 00:33:27,194
(Clattering from the kitchen)

459
00:33:30,480 --> 00:33:33,677
Here we are.
Oat straw tea and ginger pie.

460
00:33:36,800 --> 00:33:39,155
Excuse the mismatched saucers.

461
00:33:40,720 --> 00:33:44,030
- This is a new experience for me.
- Oh, wonderful!

462
00:33:44,120 --> 00:33:48,318
Try something new each day. After
all, we're given life to find it out.

463
00:33:48,400 --> 00:33:49,958
Doesn't last forever.

464
00:33:50,040 --> 00:33:51,917
You look as if you could.

465
00:33:53,480 --> 00:33:56,313
Did I tell you
I'll be 80 on Saturday?

466
00:33:56,400 --> 00:33:57,958
You don't look 80.

467
00:33:58,040 --> 00:34:02,318
That's the influence of the right
food, exercises and breathing.

468
00:34:02,400 --> 00:34:04,755
Greet the dawn with a breath of fire.

469
00:34:04,840 --> 00:34:07,673
Mmm! Hah! Hah! Hah! Hah!

470
00:34:08,200 --> 00:34:10,953
Mmm! Hah! Hah! Hah! Hah!

471
00:34:11,560 --> 00:34:13,596
Mmm! Hah! Hah...

472
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:15,797
Uh!

473
00:34:15,880 --> 00:34:17,313
Oh!

474
00:34:17,400 --> 00:34:20,437
Well, there's no question,
my body's giving out.

475
00:34:20,520 --> 00:34:24,274
I'm well into autumn. It's all gonna
be over after Saturday.

476
00:34:24,360 --> 00:34:29,115
Er, tell me about yourself. What do
you do when you aren't at funerals?

477
00:34:37,280 --> 00:34:41,239
Yes, there is definitely
a certain attraction.

478
00:34:54,600 --> 00:34:58,195
I ask you though, Harold,
is it enough?

479
00:34:59,840 --> 00:35:02,912
- What do you mean?
- Well...

480
00:35:06,080 --> 00:35:07,433
Hmm...

481
00:35:09,240 --> 00:35:11,800
I like to watch things grow.

482
00:35:19,560 --> 00:35:24,759
They... grow and bloom and...
fade and die

483
00:35:24,840 --> 00:35:26,990
and change into something else.

484
00:35:28,920 --> 00:35:30,672
Ah, life!

485
00:35:32,120 --> 00:35:36,238
(Maude) I should like to change
into a sunflower most of all.

486
00:35:36,320 --> 00:35:39,312
They're so tall and simple.

487
00:35:39,400 --> 00:35:41,550
What flower would you like to be?

488
00:35:42,640 --> 00:35:44,198
I don't know.

489
00:35:45,600 --> 00:35:48,512
- One of these maybe.
- Why do you say that?

490
00:35:50,240 --> 00:35:53,676
- Because they're all alike.
- Oh, but they're not.

491
00:35:53,760 --> 00:35:58,880
Look, see, some are smaller,
some are fatter.

492
00:35:58,960 --> 00:36:01,633
Some grow to the left,
some to the right.

493
00:36:01,720 --> 00:36:03,995
Some, even, have lost some petals.

494
00:36:04,080 --> 00:36:06,548
All kinds of observable differences.

495
00:36:07,680 --> 00:36:12,356
You see, Harold, I feel that
much of the world's sorrow

496
00:36:12,440 --> 00:36:14,715
comes from people who are this...

497
00:36:16,600 --> 00:36:20,752
yet, allow themselves
to be treated as that.

498
00:36:22,840 --> 00:36:25,195
# Well, I think it's fine

499
00:36:26,320 --> 00:36:29,232
# Building jumbo planes

500
00:36:30,640 --> 00:36:32,756
# Or taking a ride

501
00:36:33,800 --> 00:36:36,234
# On a cosmic train

502
00:36:37,800 --> 00:36:39,631
# Switch on summer

503
00:36:41,080 --> 00:36:43,196
# From a slot machine

504
00:36:44,800 --> 00:36:47,678
